Streaming SSR sends HTML progressively as data becomes available:

**Pattern 1: `loading.tsx`** (route-level Suspense):
```
app/
  dashboard/
    page.tsx      # Async data fetching
    loading.tsx   # Shows instantly while page.tsx loads
```
The shell renders immediately, data content streams in when ready.

**Pattern 2: Component-level Suspense** (granular):
```tsx
async function DashboardPage() {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Dashboard</h1>
      <Suspense fallback={<ChartSkeleton />}>
        <SlowChart />   {/* Fetches data, streams when ready */}
      </Suspense>
      <Suspense fallback={<TableSkeleton />}>
        <SlowTable />   {/* Independent, streams separately */}
      </Suspense>
    </div>
  );
}
```
The header shows instantly. Chart and table stream independently as their data resolves.

**Pattern 3: Parallel data fetching** (don't waterfall):
```tsx
async function Page() {
  // BAD: Sequential (6 seconds)
  const users = await getUsers();    // 3 sec
  const orders = await getOrders();  // 3 sec

  // GOOD: Parallel (3 seconds)
  const [users, orders] = await Promise.all([
    getUsers(),
    getOrders()
  ]);
}
```

Combine patterns: parallel fetching + component-level Suspense for perceived instant loads even with slow backends.
